HW3 Problem 5

(a) What is the probability that a randomly selected person from this population has an IQ between \(95\) and \(115\)?

\(X \sim N(\mu = 100, \sigma=10)\); equivalent notation: \(X \sim N(\mu = 100, \sigma^2=10^2)\). Denote \(F_X(x)\) - cumulative distribution function (CDF) of random variable \(X\).

Then \[ P(95 \leq X \leq 115) = F_X(115) - F_X(95). \]

We can get it from R directly using pnorm. Notes:

  • Function pnorm(q, mean = 0, sd = 1, lower.tail = TRUE) gives the cumulative distribution function (CDF) of \(N(\mu = 0,\sigma = 1)\) distribution.

  • Function pnorm(q, mean = 100, sd = 10, lower.tail = TRUE) gives the cumulative distribution function (CDF) of \(N(\mu = 100, \sigma=10)\) distribution.

  • Using pnorm(q, lower.tail = TRUE), i.e.with default value lower.tail = TRUE, gives \(P(q \leq 115) = F(115)\), whereas using pnorm(q, lower.tail = FALSE) gives \(P(q > 115) = 1 - F(115)\).

To answer the problem:

pnorm(q = 115, mean = 110, sd = 10) - pnorm(q = 95, mean = 110, sd = 10)
## [1] 0.6246553

(b) What is the \(65\)-th percentile from this distribution?

  • qnorm(p, mean = 0, sd = 1, lower.tail = TRUE) gives the quantile function \(Q(p)\), that is, it returns the value \(x\) such that \[F_X(x) = P(X \leq x) = p.\]
qnorm(p = 0.65, mean = 110, sd = 10)
## [1] 113.8532

(c) Suppose that \(5\) people are sampled from this distribution. What is the probability \(4\) (\(80\%\)) or more have IQs above \(130\)?

  • For one individual, \(P(IQ > 130)\) is
# P(IQ > 130) = 1 - P(IQ <= 130) =  1 - F(130)
p.IQ = 1 - pnorm(q = 130, mean = 110, sd = 10)
p.IQ
## [1] 0.02275013

  • The probability of seeing \(4\) or more out of \(5\) with \(IQ > 130\) can be described with Binomial distribution with parameters \(n=5\) and \(p=0.02275013\).

    • Recall: \(Binom(n,p)\) is a discrete probability distribution of the number of successes in a sequence of \(n\) independent experiments.

    • Here: denote \(Y\) result of experiment of sampling \(n=5\) people, success sampling a person with IQs above \(130\), probability o success \(p=0.02275013\).

# P(Y = 4) + P(Y = 5)
dbinom(x = 4, size = 5, prob = p.IQ) + dbinom(x = 5, size = 5, prob = p.IQ)
## [1] 1.315009e-06
# Equivalently: 
# P(Y >= 4) = 1 - P(Y <= 3) = 1 - F(3)
1 - pbinom(q = 3, size = 5, prob = p.IQ)
## [1] 1.315009e-06

(d) Suppose that \(500\) people are sampled from this distribution. What is the probability \(400 (80\%)\) or more have IQs above \(130\)?

Now \(Y \sim Binom(n = 500, p = 0.02275013)\).

# P(Y >= 400) = 1 - P(Y < 399)
1 - pbinom(q = 399, size = 500, prob = p.IQ)
## [1] 0

(e) Consider the average of \(100\) people drawn from this distribution. What is the probability that this mean is larger than \(112.5\)?

We use the Central Limit Theorem (CLT; lecture 8).

  • Consider \(X_i\), \(i=1,\ldots,n\) - a collection of iid (Independent and identically distributed) random variables with mean \(\mu\) and variance \(\sigma^2\). Denote their sample average as \(\overline{X}_n\).

  • From Central Limit Theorem we have \[P \left( \frac { \overline { X } _ { n } - \mu } { \sigma / \sqrt { n } } \leq z \right) \rightarrow \Phi ( z ),\] that is, the normalized quantity \[ \frac { \overline { X } _ { n } - \mu } { \sigma / \sqrt { n } } = \frac { \text { Estimate } - \text { Mean of estimate } } { \text { Std. Err. of estimate } } \] converges in distribution to standard normal random variable.

  • Using the above, and with certain abuse of notation, we sometimes write \[ \overline { X } _ { n } \rightarrow N \left( \mu , \frac { \sigma ^ { 2 } } { n } \right) \]

  • Then

\[ P \left( \overline { X }_n > 112.5 \right) = 1 - P \left( \overline { X }_n \leq 112.5 \right) \\ = 1 - P \left( \frac { \overline { X }_n - 110 } { 10 / \sqrt { 100 } } \leq \frac { 112.5 - 110 } { 10 / \sqrt { 100 } } \right) = 1 - P \left( Z \leq \frac { 112.5 - 110 } { 10 / \sqrt { 100 } } \right) = 1 - \Phi ( 2.5 ) \]

for \(Z \sim N(0,1)\).

1 - pnorm(q = 2.5, mean = 0, sd = 1)
## [1] 0.006209665

HW3 Problem 4

(a) What is the probability that a randomly selected person from this population has a DBP (diastolic blood pressure) less than \(90\)?

# P(DBP <= 90)
pnorm(q = 90, mean = 80, sd = sqrt(144))
## [1] 0.7976716

(b) What DBP represents the \(90\)-th, \(95\)-th and \(97.5\)-th percentiles of this distribution?

Again, qnorm(p, mean = 0, sd = 1) gives the quantile function \(Q(p)\), that is, it returns the value \(x\) such that \[F_X(x) = P(X \leq x) = p.\]

q.vec = c(0.90, 0.95, 0.975)
percentiles.out = qnorm(p = q.vec, mean = 80, sd = 12)
names(percentiles.out) = q.vec
percentiles.out
##       0.9      0.95     0.975 
##  95.37862  99.73824 103.51957

(c) What is the probability of a random person from this population having a SBP \(1\), \(2\) or \(3\) standard deviations above \(120\)? What is the corresponding probabilities for having DBPs \(1\), \(2\) or \(3\) standard deviations above \(80\)?

## SBP variable mean and sd deviation
SBP.mean <- 120
SBP.sd <- 11
# P(SBP > SBP.mean + k * SBP.sd) = 1 - P(SBP <= SBP.mean + k * SBP.sd)
1 - pnorm(q = c(SBP.mean + 1 * SBP.sd,
                SBP.mean + 2 * SBP.sd,
                SBP.mean + 3 * SBP.sd), 
          mean = SBP.mean, 
          sd = SBP.sd)
## [1] 0.158655254 0.022750132 0.001349898
## DBP variable
DBP.mean <- 80
DBP.sd <- 12
1 - pnorm(q = c(DBP.mean + 1 * DBP.sd,
                DBP.mean + 2 * DBP.sd,
                DBP.mean + 3 * DBP.sd), 
          mean = DBP.mean, 
          sd = DBP.sd)
## [1] 0.158655254 0.022750132 0.001349898
## N(0,1)
X.mean <- 0
X.sd <- 1
1 - pnorm(q = c(X.mean + 1 * X.sd,
                X.mean + 2 * X.sd,
                X.mean + 3 * X.sd), 
          mean = X.mean, 
          sd = X.sd)
## [1] 0.158655254 0.022750132 0.001349898
  • Note the rule works same for all normal distributions; you may hence use even \(N(0,1)\) to compute probability of being 1, 2 or 3 standard deviations above the mean for both SBP and DBP
## Define vector c(mean + k * standard_deviation) for N(0,1), for k=1,2,3
q.vec = c(0 + 1, 0 + 2, 0 + 3)
# 1 - P(X <= 0 + k * 1)
out <- 1 - pnorm(q = q.vec)
round(out, 4)
## [1] 0.1587 0.0228 0.0013

(d) Suppose that 10 people are sampled from this population. What is the probability that 50% (5) of them have a SBP larger than 140?

  • For one subject, the probability is \(P(SBP > 140)\)
p <- 1 - pnorm(q = 140, mean = 120, sd = 11)
  • Then, the probability that exactly five of them have SBP larger than \(140\) is
dbinom(x = 5, size = 10, prob = p)
## [1] 1.036001e-05

(e) Suppose that 1,000 people are sampled from this population. Whats the probability that 50% (500) of them have a SBP larger than 140?

Similarly to above. We use the same variable p for \(P(SBP > 140)\):

dbinom(x = 500, size = 1000, prob = p)
## [1] 0

(Note that the probability is not actually 0, but is very close to 0).

(f) If a persons SBP and DBP are independent, whats the probability that a person has a SBP larger than 140 and a DBP greater than 90? Is independence a good assumption?

  • Assuming independence of SBP and DBP, \[P(X_{SBP}>140, X_{DBP}>90) = P(X_{SBP}>140) \cdot P(X_{DBP}>90).\]
(1 - pnorm(q = 90, mean = 80, sd = 12)) * (1- pnorm(q = 140, mean = 120, sd = 11))
## [1] 0.006984006

Independence is not a good assumption here. Why?

(g) Suppose that an average of 200 people are drawn from this population. Whats the probability that this average is smaller than \(81.3\)?

(Similar as in 5e.)

For \(X_i\) being \(i-th\) person measurement of DBP, \(i=1,\ldots,200\): \[ \begin{aligned} X_i & \sim N(\mu = 80, \sigma^2 = 144) \\ \overline { X }_{200} & \sim N(\mu = 80, \sigma^2 = \frac{144}{200}) \\ & \sim N(\mu = 80, \sigma = \frac{12}{\sqrt{200}}) \\ \end{aligned} \]

\[P \left( \overline { X }_{200} < 81.3 \right) = P \left( \frac { \overline { X }_{200} - 80 } { 12 / \sqrt { 200 } } < \frac { 81.3 - 80 } { 12 / \sqrt { 200 } } \right)= P \left( Z < \frac { 81.3 - 80 } { 12 / \sqrt { 200 } } \right)= \Phi ( 1.532 )\]

for \(Z \sim N(0,1)\).

pnorm(1.532, mean = 0, sd = 1)
## [1] 0.9372388

HW3 Problem 3

(a) Whats the probability of getting \(5\) or more eggs imploding in this experiment if the true probability of implosion is \(10\%\)? Interpret this number.

  • Denote \(X\) - number of eggs imploding in this experiment.
  • Assume \(X \sim Binom(\text{size}=6, \text{pr}=p)\).
## Pr(X = 5) + Pr(X = 6)
dbinom(x = 5, size = 6, prob = 0.1) + dbinom(x = 6, size = 6, prob = 0.1) 
## [1] 5.5e-05

Equicalently, one may calculate \(Pr(X \geq 5)\) using R. Recall:

  • pbinom(q, size, prob, lower.tail=TRUE) returns \(Pr(X \leq q)\)
  • pbinom(q, size, prob, lower.tail=FALSE) returns \(Pr(X > q)\)

Here we want \(Pr(X \geq 5) = Pr(X > 4)\).

## Pr(X > 4)
pbinom(q = 4, size = 6, prob = 0.1, lower.tail = FALSE)
## [1] 5.5e-05
  • Probability of 5 or more eggs imploding is \(0.000055\).

(b) What is the maximum likelihood estimate for the probability of implosion?

In problem 1a you will derive that likelihood estimate of parameter \(p\) is \[\hat{p} = \frac{x}{n}.\]

Hence \(\hat{p} = \frac{5}{6}\).

(c) Plot and interpret the likelihood for the probability of implosion.

We use (from 1a) \[L ( p , x ) = p ^ { x } ( 1 - p ) ^ { n - x }\] and substitude what we learned from experiment: \(x = 5\) (and we have \(n = 6\)).

We plot \(L ( p , x )\) for different \(p\):

p <- seq(0, 1, length.out = 1000)
likelihoods = p^5*(1-p)^1
plot(p, likelihoods)
abline(v = 5/6, col = "blue")

We can also standardize \(L ( p , x )\) values so as the maximum of the plotted function is \(1\):

likelihoods_standard <- likelihoods/max(likelihoods)
plot(p, likelihoods_standard)
abline(v = 5/6, col = "blue")

Example of interpretation:

p[range(which(likelihoods_standard > 1/8))]
## [1] 0.4304304 0.9909910
  • Values of \(p\) from the range \((0.430, 0.991)\) are more than \(1/8\) times supported by the data than the maximally supported value \(\frac{5}{6}\) (\(= 0.833\)).
